   A TROPICAL WET FOREST IN COSTA RICA},
Journal = {ORNITOLOGIA NEOTROPICAL},
Year = {2024},
Volume = {35},
Pages = {130-133},
Abstract = {<middle dot> Long-term bird species monitoring is key to understand
   changes in species composition and assemblages. The Tirimbina Biological
   Reserve (TBR) protects a tropical wet forest in Costa Rica where bird
   species have been monitored and studied for more than 20 years. This
   study summarizes information on bird species composition generated from
   natural history, research studies, and conservation efforts carried for
   TBR. A total of 397 species are reported for TBR, where several species
   are under different IUCN's Red List conservation categories. From that
   total of species observed, 82\% are resident and 18\% are migratory.
   Also, information on species turnover after the replacement of exotic to
   native plant species in gardens, and findings from an interpretative
   bird trail are shown. TBR is a local conservation model where different
   activities such as ecotourism, science, research, and environmental
   education work together to preserve a tropical wet forest as a suitable
   habitat for many species of birds.},
